WEBVTT

00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:05.000
I am Isabel Zimmerman. I am a software engineer on the Positron team.

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:09.000
You're probably in this room because you're like, what is this Positron IDE?

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:11.000
That's the name of the talk.

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:17.000
Out of curiosity, who has heard of the Positron IDE before?

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:21.000
Oh, that is so much more than I was expecting. Welcome!

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:27.000
And if you don't know anything about the Positron IDE, this is the best room to be in.

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:31.000
I work on the Python experience. That means I write Python code.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:36.000
I think about things like, how does the autocomplete look the best for data scientists in Positron?

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:40.000
Or even things like, what UI elements will data scientists need?

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:47.000
And this is really important to me because I started out learning data science in a classroom.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:49.000
In this little class, it was called Intro to Data Science.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:55.000
I had a fantastic professor, Dr. Sanchez, and he taught me about this cycle.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:02.000
And this cycle is tidying data, you import it, you transform it, you visualize it, you model it, and you communicate it with others.

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:06.000
Many people who are data scientists, this seems pretty familiar.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:10.000
Full warning, I was writing all of R code.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:14.000
The first day in this class felt super magical.

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:22.000
I was in this RStudio IDE, and it's got a lot of different UI elements to really help you have a super seamless experience.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:25.000
I did not know anything about programming at the time.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:30.000
I made my very first plot that was not in Excel in RStudio.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:33.000
And I was able to do this all the first day.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:36.000
There was in IDE help.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:42.000
It just felt like I was very supported all the way along this data science experience.

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:49.000
And I went on to do more schooling, more learning, more classes, and RStudio was an IDE that occurred with me.

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:58.000
And I finished my degrees, and I took a job doing not R work, and I realized that this data science life cycle is the same.

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:00.000
It doesn't matter what language you're writing it in.

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:06.000
Some of you might have the same experience of learning a different language and then transferring it into what you do now.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:13.000
And a lot of those fundamentals stayed the same, but something that did change were the tools that I was using.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:15.000
I was no longer RStudio IDE.

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:24.000
I used Jupyter Notebook, just that classic notebook experience, and I ended up in JupyterLab, and I ended up in Visual Studio.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:28.000
And it felt good for a lot of reasons.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:32.000
I was using a lot of Jupyter Notebooks, and that's what these are made for.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:35.000
But it felt like something was missing.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:43.000
Some tasks sort of felt like I was stubbing my toe on the corner of a table when I was navigating through this IDE.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:47.000
And, of course, stubbing your toe is not going to ruin your day.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:51.000
Until you're stubbing your toe eight hours a day, five days a week.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:57.000
I really wasn't able to find an IDE that maximized this data science experience.

00:02:57.000 --> 00:02:59.000
I do a lot of iterative work.

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:03.000
What about tracking all the things that I run?

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:05.000
All of these things.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:11.000
So I guess a few years later, now I have hobbled my bruised feet over to working on the Positron IDE.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:21.000
And I'm hoping I can convince you all that this will give you a little bit of joy and maybe minimize some of the pain you feel with other IDEs.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:24.000
Okay, so here's the question.

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:28.000
What is Positron, and how does it support data scientists?

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:38.000
It's important to think about not only my origin story, that's not really important here, but maybe the origin story of this IDE overall.

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:42.000
So it is a multi-language IDE for data science.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:48.000
Positron is a fork of the open source VS Code, and it is customized for data science.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:51.000
This is a really classic move that other IDEs have taken.

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:57.000
If you've heard of Cursor, it's an IDE that's been forked and then used, like, really specialized for AI.

00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:01.000
It's really great because you're able to use OpenVSX extensions.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:05.000
It's pretty familiar for people if you've used VS Code before.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:07.000
It enables multi-lingual data science.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:09.000
You get to build off of this community.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:23.000
But perhaps the most important thing for what we're building is that it is a strong IDE base that we are able to customize to help do a little bit of interior decorating for data scientists.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:27.000
And that's because data science is a very iterative process.

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:32.000
You know, you want to do your quick experimentation, your writing code, your refitting models.

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:35.000
You want something that's going to support this.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:38.000
And it's important that this is made by Posit as well.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:44.000
If you're not familiar with this name, you might know us by our prior name, RStudio.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:47.000
That maybe was a bit of a leading story earlier.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:05:00.000
But what that means, that we have built RStudio, is that we have decades of knowledge of specialized IDEs specifically for data science tasks, which we know don't change depending on the language.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:05.000
So it made sense for us to, you know, branch out to this multi-language IDE.

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:08.000
We've been building Python tools for a long time.

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:12.000
We've built tools that support Julia and other data science languages.

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:21.000
So it felt right to share, you know, the joys of interior decorating and changes that we've made in RStudio with the wider community.

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:25.000
So this is your first look at Positron.

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:27.000
And it's kind of a lot in this screenshot, I'm not going to lie.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:29.000
So we'll break it down step by step.

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:34.000
If you look at the very top, this is kind of your where and what are you working on.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:37.000
So you can see here, there's like your little search pane.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:42.000
Zoom in, I don't know if you can actually zoom in, but there's a little search pane up top.

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:45.000
There's the way that you can tell what interpreter you're using.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:47.000
You can see what directory you're in.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:53.000
The classic, you know, who, what, when, where, why, how of an IDE.

00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:56.000
And of course, there's also a place for your source code.

00:05:56.000 --> 00:06:00.000
So this is another classic, you need to be able to write code somewhere.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:05.000
This is kind of the pain of the IDE that does that.

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:07.000
And right below it is a console.

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:09.000
And this is your sandbox for your code.

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:11.000
It's interactive, it's fully featured.

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:17.000
We'll dive into it a little bit more later, but you can kind of think of it as a playground for code.

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:24.000
And then the entire right-hand side, you can, of course, resize these if this looks like it's taking up too much space or whatever,

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:27.000
is context about your code.

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:32.000
So this is telling you more about the variables you've created, displaying the plots you've designed.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:34.000
It's going to render the documents you've printed.

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:36.000
And a lot more.

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:40.000
So Posit really believes in, you know, the magic, the beauty, the reproducibility,

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:45.000
all the reasons that people believe in and want to support code-first data science.

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:51.000
You know, we think this is the right choice for science is to have code that's portable, that's reproducible.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:07:02.000
But sometimes, sometimes a little bit of UI elements helps to make that writing code experience more helpful to people who are writing the code.

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:05.000
And the code that you're writing is going to go over these tasks.

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:09.000
For this talk, I'm going to step through each of these data science tasks.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:16.000
And at Posit, we're trying to kind of form, you know, what questions are data scientists thinking about each step of the way?

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:24.000
And how can we make sure that they feel fully supported throughout the entire end-to-end data science process?

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:28.000
So, of course, you start with importing, go on.

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:40.000
But maybe the elephant in the Python community room is that the beginning of data science looks sort of like this if you're writing Python code.

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:51.000
And this is a XKCD product that is really highlighting all of the many, many beautiful and somewhat successful ways you can install Python onto your machine.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:08:04.000
And if you think this is confusing, wait until you get into creating a virtual environment, all of the tens of tools to do that, and activating it, and making sure it's active in the terminal you're using, and making sure that's actually the Python script.

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:07.000
It's a mess. It's a mess. It can be confusing.

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:14.000
And that was kind of the first place that we thought, you know, maybe a little bit of UI can help people here.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:23.000
So in that who, what, when, where, how, why, all your W and H questions bar at the top, there is a interpreter selector.

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:31.000
So you can see on your screen, I'm going to keep pointing to this, your screen, that at the very top,

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:39.000
Positron will sniff out kind of all the different ways that you have Python installed, all the different environments that are available.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:45.000
There's Conda, there's Mamba, there's PyEnv, there's Venn, there's VirtualEnv, there's Poetry as well.

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:49.000
And it can be hard to wrangle these and make sure that they're all activated in the same way.

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:56.000
In Positron, you can kind of go through this UI experience and you can tell which one is active in your IDE by the little green button.

00:08:56.000 --> 00:08:58.000
It's also the one that's on the top.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:02.000
If you want to turn it off, you can click the power button.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:05.000
You can refresh your kernel right there, turn it back on.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:14.000
And this will activate your Python, whichever one you selected, in the terminal, in your console, in all your Jupyter notebooks.

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:16.000
You're also able to switch it, of course.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:28.000
But to have that unified experience where you know what Python is running at any point in time, which is somehow a harder question than you would like to admit.

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:31.000
This is kind of the first step in Positron.

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:34.000
For people who are new, go to this website.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:38.000
For other people in the room, we are now part of this community together.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:45.000
And if you can tell people to walk in and sit next to you and just point to that link, we will all have the slide.

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:48.000
Because there's no projector here.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:49.000
Okay.

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:57.000
So once you have Python chosen, you want to use this interactive console to maybe experiment with your code a little bit.

00:09:57.000 --> 00:09:59.000
And this is a live IPython console.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:02.000
It's a good place to test out quickly and see results.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:04.000
It is sort of a playground.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:10.000
It's nice as a sort of in-between between a Jupyter notebook and writing a Python script.

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:21.000
So if you want to just quickly run pieces of a Python script, you can do Command-Enter in your editor, and it will automatically send this to the console, which has been super fun for me.

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:27.000
I also manage and maintain some Python libraries.

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:31.000
And so being able to just quickly run through that code, making sure it still works.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:37.000
Before, I really copy and pasted a lot of things into a Jupyter notebook and then brought it back for development purposes.

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:42.000
So having this console at my fingertips has really been a life changer for me.

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:45.000
So I use Positron as a Python package maintainer.

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:47.000
I use Positron for building demos.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:50.000
I use Positron to build Positron.

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:54.000
There's some Inception-level things happening there.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:58.000
And a lot of that is because of the usefulness of this console.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:01.000
You can use this Command-Enter to run your code there.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:02.000
It's fully featured.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:04.000
It's connected to other pieces of the IDE.

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:10.000
We'll see a few other ways that you can visualize context about your code.

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:12.000
And it's connected to all of those.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:13.000
It has autocomplete.

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:14.000
It has syntax highlighting.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:19.000
All of the things that you would expect are fully featured in this console.

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:21.000
So we haven't even started our data science process yet.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:23.000
But we're running Python now, and that feels good.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:27.000
And we're able to switch Python environments, and that feels good.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:29.000
So we'll start by importing our data.

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:36.000
And some questions that people might be asking at this import stage is, how am I getting data into this project?

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:40.000
And it's probably starting at a database.

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:47.000
So if you have connected to a database by running some Python code that creates a cursor object in SQLAlchemy,

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:51.000
if you're familiar with that, or some sort of database connection,

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:56.000
there is a pane on that right-hand side, and this will show up.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:12:01.000
So you can see here it will get all of the tables for your database,

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:11.000
and it will show you all of the rows and the types of the columns in the database table as well.

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:13.000
And this is really helpful.

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:17.000
If you click on that little eye, the data in that database table will automatically populate.

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:19.000
You don't have to run any code.

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:24.000
It's one of those places where code for data science is useful for the reproducibility part,

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:25.000
but sometimes there's some rough edges.

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:28.000
You just want to take a quick look at something.

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:32.000
And this is a nice place to kind of ease that transition.

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:38.000
Not only can you view your database information here, you can also manage your connection.

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:40.000
So you can refresh a connection.

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:41.000
You can disconnect.

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:45.000
If you want to disconnect from your database, it can also reconnect.

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:51.000
It will store the knowledge of how to manage this database connection.

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:53.000
And it's currently supported for SQLite.

00:12:53.000 --> 00:13:00.000
If you have other ideas, we would love to hear from you on GitHub.

