00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:45.000
rather than going out to the Internet or trying to scroll through RST

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:48.000
or something like that.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:50.000
This is something I also use as a package developer a lot

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:53.000
to really make sure that people can navigate

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:55.000
through my docs efficiently.

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:58.000
So if you see on this screenshot,

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:00.000
these are interlinked natively.

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:03.000
So if you click from data frame records,

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:05.000
you can navigate to that page instead.

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:07.000
There's also examples that have a little copy button

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:09.000
that you can run on the console.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:12.000
We support NumPy, space style doc strings,

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:15.000
as well as Google and ePi or epi text,

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:19.000
depending on how you're supposed to pronounce that.

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:21.000
There's also plots panes.

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:25.000
So this is another place where we believe

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:29.000
that data visualization is a very large part of data science.

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:32.000
And so we had a dedicated space for this.

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:34.000
And this is important because if you're iterating on a plot,

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:37.000
like here, sometimes you're writing your subplots

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:40.000
and you're adding things onto this data visualization

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:44.000
and it will update as you go.

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:47.000
But of course, not all of our plots are perfect.

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:49.000
We're not ChatGPT.

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:51.000
And this comes in handy when you have a lot of plots.

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:55.000
You kind of get this thumbnail experience.

00:17:55.000 --> 00:17:57.000
And you can see the different iterations.

00:17:57.000 --> 00:17:58.000
You're able to resize them.

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:03.000
You're able to export them as PDF or PNG or TIFF or SVG

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:05.000
or a number of different ways.

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:09.000
And one of my favorite buttons in Positron just as a whole

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:12.000
is there's a copy to clipboard button

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:15.000
because we all know that plots always end up being exported

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:19.000
into a Word document.

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:23.000
The final step of our data science experience is communicating.

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:28.000
And we have a viewer pane, again, on this right-hand side,

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:30.000
to view your locally running content.

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:34.000
It's fully interactive and it is right in this IDE.

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:36.000
So you can view local host URLs.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:38.000
Again, if we're in New York, I thought Word almost seemed

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:42.000
like an appropriate thing to be showing in this viewer pane.

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:44.000
This is a Streamlit app.

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:50.000
And if you are running Streamlit apps, panel, radio,

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:54.000
Shiny, FastAPI, or Flask, that little play button in the top corner

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:57.000
is going to be running this app in your terminal

00:18:57.000 --> 00:19:00.000
and automatically opening it up in the viewer pane.

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:02.000
So you don't have to write the same command over and over again.

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:05.000
You can just click your button.

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:09.000
And it will automatically populate in this viewer pane.

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:11.000
I also had to add a little bit of slide section here.

00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:13.000
I developed these slides in Positron.

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:15.000
They are all markdown.

00:19:15.000 --> 00:19:20.000
And so here was me in a non-purple background version of my slides.

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:23.000
In Positron, as I was updating them, I would just save.

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:26.000
It automatically re-rendered in this viewer pane.

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:29.000
And it was really just a delightful experience.

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:31.000
I get to put my slides on GitHub afterwards.

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:35.000
It feels great for me to have this portfolio of slides.

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:38.000
I'm just a big Portal fan. I think it's great.

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:43.000
And this viewer pane really helps me to be able to develop things quickly.

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:47.000
So this is what Positron looks like.

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:49.000
This has been a very fast walkthrough.

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:51.000
It is super fun to play around with.

00:19:51.000 --> 00:19:53.000
We tried to make it intuitive for people.

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:55.000
It should feel friendly to people.

00:19:55.000 --> 00:19:58.000
You should be able to kind of download it.

00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:02.000
Python should be running as long as it's on your machine.

00:20:02.000 --> 00:20:04.000
And it's something we've been really proud of at Posit.

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:07.000
And we hope that people will try it out.

00:20:07.000 --> 00:20:09.000
So what else is happening with Positron?

00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:13.000
Up next is going to be updating the Jupyter Notebook experience.

00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:16.000
We think that there's a lot of UI elements that can be adjusted

00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:19.000
to make things a little bit easier to maybe connect to kernels

00:20:19.000 --> 00:20:23.000
or go through code in a Jupyter Notebook.

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:26.000
I do have to say, Positron is an early stage project.

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:31.000
We have just released it to the public as of three or four months ago,

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:34.000
whenever August was.

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:36.000
But it's ready for real work.

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:37.000
We've spent a lot of time on it.

00:20:37.000 --> 00:20:39.000
We have a lot of miles on it.

00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:42.000
But if there are some weird things happening,

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:45.000
feel free to visit us on GitHub.

00:20:45.000 --> 00:20:46.000
That is where it is available.

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:48.000
You can download it from GitHub.

00:20:48.000 --> 00:20:52.000
If you want a step-by-step of how to download it, you can get started.

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:55.000
It's available at positron.posit.co.

00:20:55.000 --> 00:20:58.000
It will take you through the whole process.

00:20:58.000 --> 00:21:00.000
And thank you.

00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:04.000
Applause

